As shown in Fig.~\ref{chipptoH1}, the cross section $\sigma(pp \to H_1^0)$ ranges from about $10$ to $100$~fb in the parameter space of interest to us.  To get a diphoton cross section of a few fb, one expects that ${\cal B}(H_1^0 \to \gamma\gamma)$ has to reach at least the percent level.  But, as shown in Table~\ref{widthBR}, the diphoton branching ratio is generally off by 2 to 3 orders of magnitude in the case of larger $v_\Delta$ and by 1 to 2 orders of magnitude for smaller $v_\Delta$.  Therefore, in the allowed parameter space, we cannot obtain sufficient cross section to fit the observation made by ATLAS and CMS, although the total width of $H_1^0$ is generally a few tens of GeV.  Depending on $(v_\Delta,\alpha)$, the maximum diphoton cross section at 13-TeV LHC is predicted to be {\cal O}(10) to {\cal O}($10^2$)~ab.




\section{Conclusions \label{sec:summary}}



Even though the data are yet conclusive, the recent observation of diphoton excess around the mass of 750~GeV in LHC Run-II by both the ATLAS and CMS Collaborations inspires us to examine whether the singlet Higgs boson in the custodial Higgs triplet model can serve as a good candidate.  Such a model is motivated to give Majorana mass to neutrinos through $SU(2)_L$ Higgs triplet fields while preserving the custodial symmetry.  Under the $SU(2)_L$ symmetry, the exotic Higgs bosons originating from the triplet fields are decomposed into a singlet, a triplet, and a quintet, with the former two being able to mix with the corresponding representations from the standard model Higgs doublet field.  When the triplet fields acquires an ${\cal O}(10)$~GeV vacuum expectation value as induced by the breakdown of electroweak symmetry, the exotic Higgs bosons exhibit novel collider phenomena.


Based on an earlier study of comprehensive parameter scan for viable mass spectra, we show that a 750-GeV $H_1^0$ falls well within the allowed space.  Imposing the constraints of 8-TeV search data for the assumed mass, we find that $10~{\rm GeV} \lesssim v_\Delta \lesssim 35~{\rm GeV}$ and $-18^\circ \lesssim \alpha \lesssim -5^\circ$, where $v_\Delta$ denotes the triplet vacuum expectation value and $\alpha$ is the mixing angle between the heavy Higgs singlet and the 125-GeV Higgs boson.  Moreover, we point out that a definite mass hierarchy, $m_{H_1} = 750~{\rm GeV} > m_{H_3} > m_{H_5}$, emerges among the exotic Higgs bosons in the model.  Such information enables us to make more definite predictions about how the exotic Higgs bosons decay.  In particular, we find that even the maximum diphoton production through $H_1^0$ is still off the observed excess by 2 to 3 orders of magnitude.  It is therefore impossible to use the singlet Higgs boson in the custodial Higgs triplet model to explain the 750-GeV diphoton excess observed in LHC Run-II.





